GeneralExplanationGrp.MediumExplanationTxt: 1. Leadership for Better Health - Programs and activities to bring together leaders from all walks of life, including the health professions, and develop their skills to lead the change necessary to build a Culture of Health. Includes programs that develop health policy scholars, encourage youth to pursue health careers, and partner community leaders with researchers. $ 8,615,628 2. General Outreach and Support - Programs which support improving health care value, promoting prevention, growing the field of health and health care leadership, supporting communications and policy projects, and synthesizing and spreading research and evaluation findings through the web, social media and other means. $ 7,740,324 3. Healthy Children and Families - Programs and activities to support strategic communications activities that will ensure all families, no matter their background, have access to the resources they need to raise thriving children, fostering healthy development from a child's earliest years. $ 7,590,495 4. Healthy Communities - Programs, projects, and activities to create the conditions that allow communities and their residents to reach their best possible well-being. $ 7,467,924 5. Other Targeted Programs - Programs, projects, and non-lobbying activities to inform the policymaking process in Washington, state capitals, and communities at all levels of government by funding and sharing high quality, evidence-based, nonpartisan reports and analyses that can help shape and implement health and health equity policies. In addition, programs, projects, and activities to; to achieve health equity by ensuring that everyone has a fair and just opportunity to live the healthiest life possible; to strengthen the ability of health and health care systems to work together to recognize and meet the goals and needs of the people they serve; to explore emerging trends and cutting edge ideas that can help the foundation anticipate, influence and adapt to an evolving culture; to find and adapt ideas from other countries that could help improve our health here at home; to support locally-based projects that promote the health and health care of New Jerseyans; and to support research, evaluation, learning and communications efforts that can improve the nation's health. $18,360,933 Total direct charitable activities during the tax year. $49,775,304
